04743nam a22007455i 9780691229218DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021934434  a97806912292187 a10.1515/97806912292182doi  a(DE-B1597)581231  a(OCoLC)1259320156  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0500002bisacsh04a373.742721 aKhan, Shamus Rahman, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrivilege :bThe Making of an Adolescent Elite at St. Paul's School /cShamus Rahman Khan. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in Cultural Sociology ;v12100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the 2021 Edition -- tIntroduction: Democratic Inequality -- t1. The New Elite -- t2. Finding One's Place -- t3. The Ease of Privilege -- t4. Gender and the Performance of Privilege -- t5. Learning Beowulf and Jaws -- tConclusion -- tMethodological and Theoretical Reflections -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs one of the most prestigious high schools in the nation, St. Paul's School in Concord, New Hampshire, has long been the exclusive domain of America's wealthiest sons. But times have changed. Today, a new elite of boys and girls is being molded at St. Paul's, one that reflects the hope of openness but also the persistence of inequality.In Privilege, Shamus Khan returns to his alma mater to provide an inside look at an institution that has been the private realm of the elite for the past 150 years. He shows that St. Paul's students continue to learn what they always have--how to embody privilege. Yet, while students once leveraged the trappings of upper-class entitlement, family connections, and high culture, current St. Paul's students learn to succeed in a more diverse environment. To be the future leaders of a more democratic world, they must be at ease with everything from highbrow art to everyday life--from Beowulf to Jaws--and view hierarchies as ladders to scale. Through deft portrayals of the relationships among students, faculty, and staff, Khan shows how members of the new elite face the opening of society while still preserving the advantages that allow them to rule.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBoarding schoolsxSocial aspectszNew HampshirezConcord. 0aBoarding schoolszNew HampshirezConcordxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073912140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691229218zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691229218423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691229218/original  a978-3-11-073912-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075418-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2021  aZ